      "evidence": [
        "broadcast loop/state/runtime layers rely on deep function-typed seam structs and singleton fallbacks (`resolveBroadcastStateRuntime`, `resolveBroadcastLoopRuntime`, `resolveBroadcastStateTransitionRuntime`), so callers can omit dependencies and silently use shared global state instead of explicit composition.",
        "ship workflow and orchestration runtimes contain repeated section-specific persistence wrappers where each method is a near-identical pass-through to a generic section updater (`persistShipUrbitRuntimeConfig`, `persistShipUrbitNetworkConfig`, etc. vs `persistShipUrbitSection`).",
        "wifi runtime mixes command strategies: `runCommand(\"nmcli\", ...)` for simple queries while also carrying direct library-backed client methods (`NewWifiClient`, `ClientInterfacesFn`, `ClientBSSFn`), and one path shells out through `ExecCommand(\"sh\", \"-c\", ...)` with hard-coded text pipeline parsing."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "confidence": "high",
      "sub_axes": {
        "abstraction_leverage": 56.0,
        "indirection_cost": 42.0,
        "interface_honesty": 61.0
      }
    }
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "shell_command_leaky_wifi_abstraction",
      "summary": "Wi-Fi runtime leaks host command-line surface through shell-parsed command strings instead of a typed command abstraction.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_methods.go",
        "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_api.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`wifiDevices` builds one shell command string and parses free-form output via `sh -c \"nmcli device status | grep wifi | awk '{print $1}'\"`, creating tight coupling to shell syntax and output formatting.",
        "`resolveDevice` and callsites in `wifi_runtime_api.go` consume this path directly (`runtime.primaryWifiDevice()`), so all consumers inherit that command-semantics coupling.",
        "The same runtime type also carries both command API (`runCommand` / `exec.Command`) and library APIs (`wifi.New`, `ClientInterfacesFn`, `ClientBSSFn`), indicating inconsistent abstraction boundaries."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Replace the shell pipeline path with a typed nmcli execution API that accepts argument slices and a structured parse layer, and reuse the same abstraction path across all Wi-Fi queries; keep `sh` execution only as a narrow compatibility layer with its own clearly bounded seam.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "command_shell_abstraction_leak"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "runtime_section_persistence_wrappers",
      "summary": "Multiple one-off section persistence wrappers add abstraction overhead without unique behavior and obscure the real intent of the update API.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/shipworkflow/operations_runtime.go",
        "goseg/docker/orchestration/runtime_ops.go",
        "goseg/config/config.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`persistShipUrbitRuntimeConfig`, `persistShipUrbitNetworkConfig`, `persistShipUrbitScheduleConfig`, `persistShipUrbitFeatureConfig`, `persistShipUrbitWebConfig`, and `persistShipUrbitBackupConfig` each perform only a `persistShipUrbitSection` adapter call and differ only by constant section enum and type wrapper.",
        "`RuntimeUrbitOps` exposes separate function fields per section (`UpdateUrbitRuntimeConfigFn`, `UpdateUrbitNetworkConfigFn`, …) while `defaultRuntimeUrbit` maps each to a dedicated direct callback on config, duplicating a section-routing layer.",
        "This indirection is mirrored in callers that define tiny wrappers rather than composing a small generic section-update API."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce one generic section-update abstraction at the workflow layer (e.g., `persistShipUrbitSectionConfig(patp, section, mutate)` and one runtime callback) and keep section-specific adapters as tiny constants only at the public boundary if needed.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "thin_wrapper_farm"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "broadcast_singleton_fallback_seams",
      "summary": "Broadcast state/runtime abstractions silently collapse to package singletons, weakening seam enforcement and making behavior implicit.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/broadcast/state.go",
        "goseg/broadcast/loop.go",
        "goseg/broadcast/transitions.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`broadcastStateRuntime` resolution falls back to `defaultBroadcastStateRuntime` whenever runtime args are omitted or nil (`resolveBroadcastStateRuntime` / `resolveDefaultBroadcastStateRuntime`).",
        "The same fallback pattern exists in loop and transition resolvers (`resolveBroadcastLoopRuntime`, `resolveBroadcastStateTransitionRuntime`), so callers can accidentally bypass injected dependencies.",
        "This creates hidden shared mutable state across tests and runtime paths, despite the presence of seam structs intended for explicit injection."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Remove implicit singleton fallback from domain transition/loop functions and require explicit runtime context at call boundaries; keep a single explicit default constructor at application startup only.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "implicit_singleton_seams"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "command-line shells treated as abstraction boundary in system runtime",
      "thin wrapper proliferation around a single section-upsert mechanism",
      "singleton-based dependency fallback masking explicit runtime composition"
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "harder mocking and test determinism in wifi and broadcast loops",
      "increased file-level boilerplate for section config updates with limited behavioral gain",
      "implicit cross-call coupling via shared broadcast runtime state"
    ],
    "possible_false_positives": [
      "some wrappers may be intentional API stability shims for external consumers",
      "broadcast singleton fallback could be relied on by existing tests expecting zero-config defaults"
    ]
  }
}


